The Use of Child Physical Punishment in Upbringing and Its Link to Economic Development

Child punishment as a method of raising has been widely debated across cultures and countries . Some countries view it as a necessary tool for raising and teaching discipline, while others consider it harmful to a childâs development. We will discover weather countries with higher support for physical punishment often have lower GDP per capita, within the countries is there a specific gender who is more likely use this method.

Life Expectancy Growth vs.Â GDP per Capita

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *
from google.colab import drive



# Load and clean data
file_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/report/LifeExpectancyGrowthvsGDPperCapita_unicef_m_data.csv"
df = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# Drop rows with missing values in key columns
df = df.dropna(subset=[
    "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)",
    "Life expectancy at birth, total (years)",
    "Year of Year"
])

# Group by year and average the values
avg_df = df.groupby("Year of Year").agg({
    "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)": "mean",
    "Life expectancy at birth, total (years)": "mean"
}).reset_index()

# Rename columns for easier access
avg_df.columns = ["Year", "GDP_per_capita", "Life_Expectancy"]

# Reshape to long format
long_df = pd.melt(
    avg_df,
    id_vars="Year",
    value_vars=["GDP_per_capita", "Life_Expectancy"],
    var_name="Measure",
    value_name="Value"
)


# # Separate data for dual-axis simulation
long_gdp = long_df[long_df["Measure"] == "GDP_per_capita"].copy()
long_life = long_df[long_df["Measure"] == "Life_Expectancy"].copy()

# # Normalize Life Expectancy to match GDP scale range for visual dual-axis
life_min, life_max = long_life["Value"].min(), long_life["Value"].max()
gdp_min, gdp_max = long_gdp["Value"].min(), long_gdp["Value"].max()

scale_factor = (gdp_max - gdp_min) / (life_max - life_min)
offset = gdp_min - life_min * scale_factor
long_life["Value"] = long_life["Value"] * scale_factor + offset

# Combine adjusted data
combined_df = pd.concat([long_gdp, long_life])

# Plot using plotnine
graph = (
    ggplot(combined_df, aes(x="Year", y="Value", color="Measure")) +
    geom_line(size=1.5) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', linetype="dashed", se=False) +


     scale_color_manual(
        values={
            "GDP_per_capita": "#D55E00",        # burnt orange
            "Life_Expectancy": "#FFC95F"        # yellow
        }
    ) +
#scale_color_manual(values=colors) +
    scale_y_continuous(
        name="Avg. GDP per capita",
        labels=lambda l: [f"${int(x):,}" for x in l],
        limits=(0, None),
        breaks=range(0, int(combined_df["Value"].max()) + 1, 2000)

    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name="Years",
        limits=(1955, 2025),
        breaks=range(1950, 2025, 5)
 ) +
    labs(

        x="Years"
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        legend_title=element_blank(),
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight='bold', ha='center')

    )
)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig = graph.draw()
fig.set_size_inches(15, 10)
fig

This graph illustrates the relationship between average GDP per capita in yellow and average life expectancy at birth in brown over time, spanning from the mid-20th century to the present.

The left y-axis represents GDP per capita, while the right y-axis represents life expectancy in years. Both indicators show a steady upward trend, indicating that as economic prosperity increases, life expectancy also improves. The dashed trendlines highlight the overall growth trajectory for each variable. Significant acceleration in GDP per capita growth is noticeable after the 1990s, which aligns with major global economic developments. Life expectancy follows a similar pattern, with a notable rise after 2000, reflecting advancements in healthcare, sanitation, and overall living conditions.

This visualization underscores the positive correlation between economic development and improvements in public health over time.

This graph showcases the six countries with the highest average GDP per capita over time. Qatar shows a significant rise, peaking above $100,000 before fluctuating. Other countries such as Uruguay, Barbados, and Trinidad & Tobago exhibit steady growth but remain at lower levels compared to Qatar.

The overall trend indicates that wealthier nations have experienced continuous economic growth, with some volatility.

Bottom 5 countries with Lowest GDP per capita (1960â2023)

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *

# Load GDP per capita time-series data
df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/report/Lowest GDP per capita_data.csv")

# Define custom shades of brown for consistent gradient look
shades = ["#feedde", "#fdbe85", "#fd8d3c", "#e6550d", "#a63603"]

# Ensure order for consistency if needed
df["Country"] = pd.Categorical(df["Country"], categories=sorted(df["Country"].unique()), ordered=True)

# Plot line chart
graph = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x="Year of Year", y="Avg. GDP per capita", color="Country")) +
    geom_line(size=1) +
    scale_color_manual(values=shades) +
    labs(

        x="Years",
        y="Avg. GDP per capita"
    ) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels=lambda l: [f"${int(x):,}" for x in l]) +
    theme_minimal()

)

# Save to file
# graph.save("/mnt/data/lowest_gdp_per_capita_plot.png", width=12, height=10, dpi=300)
graph.draw()
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig = graph.draw()
fig.set_size_inches(15, 10)
fig

This line chart displaying the GDP per capita trends of the five countries with the lowest GDP per capita from 1960 to 2023. The y-axis represents the average GDP per capita in USD, while the x-axis represents the years from 1960 to 2023.

The five countries represented are Afghanistan, Burundi, Central African Republic, Democratic Republic of the Congo, and Niger. GDP per capita has fluctuated significantly over time, with some periods showing sharp increases or declines. There is an overall upward trend in GDP per capita for most of the countries, although the levels remain low.

Male vs.Â female perspectives based on High GDP per capita

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *

# Load preprocessed high GDP gender data
df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/report/MaleFemale_HighGDP_Corrected.csv")

# Plot bar chart
graph = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x="Sex", y="Avg. Obs Value", fill="Country")) +
    geom_col(position="dodge") +
    facet_wrap("~Country") +
    scale_fill_brewer(type="qual", palette="Dark2") +
    scale_y_continuous(expand=(0, 0), limits=(0, df["Avg. Obs Value"].max() + 5)) +
    scale_x_discrete(expand=(0.5, 0)) +  # tighter x spacing but not completely zero

    labs(

        y="Avg. Punishment Support"
    )


)

graph.draw()
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig = graph.draw()
fig.set_size_inches(8, 5)
fig

The bar chart shows that in Trinidad and Tobago, support for child physical punishment is higher among females than males but remains relatively low overall, while in the Turks and Caicos Islands, only females are represented, with significant support.

Overall, high-GDP countries show lower support for child punishment, likely due to progressive views influenced by better education, legal frameworks, and alternative discipline methods.

In the next graph ,we will compare the relationship of low GDP countries and the different genders support.

Male vs.Â Female perspectives based on Low GDP per capita

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *

# Load preprocessed low GDP gender data
df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/report/MaleFemale (Low  GDP Countries)_data.csv")

# Plot bar chart
graph = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x="Sex", y="Avg. Obs Value", fill="Country")) +
    geom_col(position="dodge") +
    facet_wrap("~Country",
  nrow = 1,
  ncol = 4)+
  scale_fill_brewer(type='qual', palette='Set2') +

scale_y_continuous(expand=(0, 0), limits=(0, df["Avg. Obs Value"].max() + 5)) +
    scale_x_discrete(expand=(0.5, 0)) +  # tighter x spacing but not completely zero
    labs(

        y="Avg. Punishment Support"
    )


)
graph.draw()
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig = graph.draw()
fig.set_size_inches(15, 10)
fig

The bar chart indicates that support for child physical punishment is generally high in low-GDP countries, with variations between genders.

In Afghanistan and the Democratic Republic of the Congo, both males and females show strong support, with females slightly more supportive. In Burundi, support is low but slightly higher among females, while in the Central African Republic, both genders show nearly equal support.

The child punishment support in low-GDP nations is likely influenced by cultural norms, lack of awareness about alternative raising methods, and limited education on child rights, driven by traditional beliefs and socio-economic challenges

Summary

The visualizations collectively highlight the strong relationship between economic development and various social indicators, including life expectancy and attitudes toward child punishment as a form of raising. The wealthier nations generally show lower support for child punishment, suggesting that economic stability fosters progressive views on raising children. However, some high-GDP countries like Qatar still exhibit notable support for punishment, maybe due to cultural factor . Conversely, nations with low GDP per capita tend to have stronger support for punishment child-rearing practices, with notable gender differences in perspectives, particularly in lower-income regions where women often express greater support for punishment for raising children.
